Avulsion: The Rapid Abandonment of a River Channel

Plumes of [sediment](/Sediment) unfurl into the vast expanse of the [ocean](/Ocean) from the multiple [mouths](/River_mouth) of the [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River)'s distinctive [bird's-foot delta](/Bird%27s-foot_delta). This ceaseless delivery of sediment is the very architect of the delta, enabling its relentless advance into the sea. As this landmass extends further offshore, a critical change occurs: the [channel slope](/Grade_(slope)) diminishes, and the riverbed begins to [aggrade](/Aggradation). These conditions create a fertile ground for avulsion, the dramatic process where a river abandons its established course for a new one.

In the intricate fields of [sedimentary geology](/Sedimentary_geology) and fluvial [geomorphology](/Geomorphology), avulsion is defined as the diversion of a river's flow from its existing channel into a new course. This occurs through a bifurcation, essentially a splitting of the main channel. Avulsions can be absolute, where all the water abandons the old path for the new, or they can be partial, with only a segment of the flow migrating. Historically, it was believed that avulsions were solely triggered by channel slopes that were significantly less steep than an alternative route the river could take – a notion of a "slope advantage" driving the change. &#91;1&#93; However, contemporary understanding reveals a more complex interplay of factors. It's now recognized that the upstream channel's [planform](/Channel_pattern), the precise [cross-sectional geometry](/Channel_cross-sectional_geometry) at a bifurcation point, and even obstructions such as accumulations of wood debris or [beaver dams](/Beaver_dam) can all influence the speed and development of an avulsion. &#91;2&#93;&#91;3&#93;&#91;4&#93;&#91;5&#93;

Deltaic and Net-Depositional Settings: Where Rivers Meet the Sea

Avulsions are a particularly common phenomenon in [river deltas](/River_delta). Here, the river's energy dissipates as it encounters the ocean, leading to the deposition of [sediment](/Sediment). This deposition naturally occurs where [channel gradients](/Grade_(slope)) are already minimal. This process is often referred to as delta switching. &#91;6&#93;

As the river deposits its sediment load, it constructs individual [deltaic lobes](/Deltaic_lobe), extending them outward into the sea. The iconic bird's-foot delta of the [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River), characterized by its prominent [sediment](/Sediment) plumes, serves as a prime example. With each advance of a deltaic lobe, the river channel lengthens, but its overall change in elevation remains constant. This results in a progressively lower [slope](/Slope) for the river channel. This reduced gradient destabilizes the channel for a couple of key reasons. Firstly, the force of [gravity](/Gravity) naturally compels water to seek the most direct downward path. If the river breaches its natural [levees](/Levees), perhaps during a [flood](/Flood), it can spill onto a new course that offers a shorter, and therefore steeper, route to the ocean, achieving a more stable gradient. &#91;2&#93; Secondly, the reduced slope leads to a decrease in the [shear stress](/Shear_stress) exerted on the riverbed. This diminished stress promotes the deposition of more sediment within the channel itself, causing the channel bed to rise relative to the adjacent [floodplain](/Floodplain). This elevation increase makes it progressively easier for the river to overtop its levees and carve a new channel that offers a steeper trajectory to the sea.

Once this avulsion occurs, the newly formed channel becomes the conduit for sediment delivery, initiating the construction of a new deltaic lobe. &#91;7&#93;&#91;8&#93; The previously active delta, now deprived of significant sediment supply, gradually begins to subside. &#91;9&#93;

This cyclical process is intrinsically linked to the complex [distributary network](/Distributary) of channels that often characterizes a mature river delta. When a river repeatedly switches its course through avulsion, some flow may persist in the abandoned channels. Over extended periods, these recurring channel-switching events contribute to the intricate, branching pattern observed within river deltas. &#91;10&#93;

The process of [subsidence](/Subsidence) within the delta, coupled with potential [sea-level rise](/Sea-level_rise), can further exacerbate backwater conditions and lead to increased deposition within the delta. This accumulated sediment can effectively fill the older channels, leaving a distinct geological record of past channel avulsions within [sedimentary basins](/Sedimentary_basin). On average, it's estimated that an avulsion will occur once the river channel's bed has aggraded to a point where the channel is elevated above the surrounding floodplain by a depth equivalent to one channel width. At this threshold, sufficient [hydraulic head](/Hydraulic_head) exists to facilitate a breach of the natural levees, triggering an avulsion. &#91;11&#93;&#91;12&#93;

Erosional Avulsions: When Erosion Carves a New Path

Rivers can also undergo avulsion through the process of erosion, where a new, more direct channel is carved through the landscape. This typically occurs during significant flood events, especially when the gradient of the newly eroded channel is considerably steeper than that of the original course. If the new channel's slope is roughly comparable to the old one, a partial avulsion might ensue, with flow continuing in both channels. &#91;1&#93;

A compelling instance of an erosional avulsion is the 2006 event involving the [Suncook River](/Suncook_River) in [New Hampshire](/New_Hampshire). Intense rainfall caused water levels to surge. The river's flow backed up behind an old mill dam, creating a shallow pool that eventually overtopped a sand and gravel quarry. This breach connected to a downstream section of the river, rapidly carving a new, shorter channel at a rate of 25–50 meters per hour. &#91;13&#93; The vast quantities of sediment mobilized by this erosional avulsion subsequently contributed to a depositionally-driven meander cutoff further downstream. This occurred as the excess sediment built up around the meander bend, effectively elevating the channel bed to near the level of the floodplain. &#91;14&#93;

Another notable example is the [Cheslatta River](/Cheslatta_River) in [British Columbia](/British_Columbia), once a minor tributary of the [Nechako River](/Nechako_River). In the 1950s, the Cheslatta River was repurposed as the [spillway](/Spillway) for the newly constructed [Nechako Reservoir](/Nechako_Reservoir). The sheer volume of water discharged from the reservoir vastly exceeded the Cheslatta River's original flow, leading to substantial erosion in its upper valley and the deposition of this scoured sediment in the lower valley. The immense reservoir spills triggered avulsions in the lower Cheslatta River in 1961 and again in 1972, forcing the river to carve new routes towards the Nechako River and depositing a significant fan of sediment, known as the Cheslatta Fan, into the main river. Following the 1972 event, a [cofferdam](/Cofferdam) was constructed to guide the river back to its original course. &#91;15&#93;

Meander Cutoffs: A Minor Avulsion

A specific type of minor avulsion is known as a [meander cutoff](/Meander_cutoff). This occurs when a pronounced bend, or meander, in a river is breached by floodwaters. The flow effectively connects the two closest points of the meander loop, creating a straighter, new channel. This phenomenon is more likely to happen when the ratio between the existing channel slope and the potential slope of the avulsed channel is less than approximately 1/5. &#91;2&#93;

The Occurrence of Avulsion

Avulsions are typically events that unfold during significant flood periods, when rivers possess the immense power required to dramatically reshape the landscape. It's also worth noting that the [dam removal](/Dam_removal) process could potentially initiate or contribute to avulsions.

The progression of an avulsion usually occurs in a downstream to upstream manner, driven by [head cutting erosion](/Head_cut_(stream_geomorphology)). When a bank of the active stream is breached, a new channel, or trench, begins to form within the existing floodplain. This new course may cut through existing floodplain deposits or, alternatively, reoccupy a segment of an older, abandoned channel. &#91;16&#93;

Investigations into avulsions have frequently focused on deltas and coastal plain environments. These studies have explored the roles of obstructions, such as extensive [log-jams](/Log_jam), and potential [tectonic influences](/Tectonics) in triggering these channel shifts. &#91;17&#93;